      Larry Fink
   =20
 =20
Today=E2=80=99s Wall Street Journal has a profile of Larry Fink, the chief =
executive officer of BlackRock Inc., and how he =E2=80=9CWants to Save the =
World (and Make Money Doing It).=E2=80=9D We have talked a lot about BlackR=
ock=E2=80=99s  environmental efforts, and about=C2=A0various  controversies=
=C2=A0around them. There is a strange tension at BlackRock where, on the on=
e hand, it is obviously good for BlackRock=C2=A0to be viewed as a powerful =
force that can tell companies what to do, but on the other hand it is also =
dangerous.It is good for them mostly in the=C2=A0simple sense that BlackRoc=
k and Fink=C2=A0want companies to do certain things, and so it is helpful t=
o be powerful so that BlackRock can tell them what to do and they=E2=80=99l=
l listen:As steward for millions of investors, BlackRock wields vast shareh=
older voting power, which it uses either to back managements or to prod the=
m in new directions.Today, Mr. Fink is telling CEOs that companies must pre=
pare for a scaleback of fossil fuels, and that the private sector should wo=
rk with governments to do so. He warns of the disruption climate change cou=
ld cause both the economy and financial markets, but sees historic investme=
nt opportunity in the energy shift. It=E2=80=99s a point he has made to con=
ferences in Davos, Venice, Riyadh and Glasgow over the past year. ...BlackR=
ock in 2012 released the first of Mr. Fink=E2=80=99s annual letters to CEOs=
, which have become required reading for many chief executives. He uses the=
 letters to prod, scold and push companies to disclose more about how they =
provide for workers, the environment and the community at large.=C2=A0Big s=
hareholders like BlackRock don=E2=80=99t have, like, a button they can push=
 to make companies do what they want. The process of using share ownership =
to influence companies is  complicated and leaky; Fink can=E2=80=99t just g=
ive orders and have them carried out. Being perceived as powerful is good f=
or him; it makes it more likely that, when he gives suggestions, they=E2=80=
=99ll be treated as orders.=C2=A0It is bad, though, in the sense that when =
you say =E2=80=9Cthere=E2=80=99s one guy who can tell the CEOs of every pub=
lic company in the world what to do,=E2=80=9D that sounds =E2=80=A6=C2=A0yo=
u know =E2=80=A6=C2=A0worrying? For one thing, traditionally antitrust law =
regulates that sort of thing. We have  talked a  lot around here about  the=
 theory that common ownership of multiple companies in the same industry by=
 the same large diversified shareholders might be bad for competition, and =
the strongest argument against that theory is generally =E2=80=9Cwell in pr=
actice it=E2=80=99s not like the big index-fund managers actually call up C=
EOs and tell them how to run their businesses.=E2=80=9D Except that Fink ki=
nd of does! The letters are a bit of an antitrust headache. The Journal not=
es:Starting in 2019, his letters drew the attention of a Federal Trade Comm=
ission official, Bilal Sayyed, who showed some to colleagues at the antitru=
st agency and asked them to think about whether BlackRock was affecting com=
petition in industries.=C2=A0Also, though, this particular role =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0telling the world how to address climate change, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0=
seems so important that it is weird to put it in the hands of one guy, one =
guy who was not exactly=C2=A0elected=C2=A0to the job. =E2=80=9CHanging over=
 the discussion is the argument that Mr. Fink is taking on a role better le=
ft to elected representatives,=E2=80=9D says the Journal, and: =E2=80=9CRea=
l-estate investor Sam Zell said to CNBC a few years ago: =E2=80=98I didn=E2=
=80=99t know Larry Fink had been made God.=E2=80=99=E2=80=9DNow, in a sense=
, Fink was=C2=A0elected to this job: He founded BlackRock, he continues to =
run it because the board and shareholders continue to have faith in him, an=
d BlackRock runs $10 trillion of client money because the clients like what=
 he is selling. Capital markets are=C2=A0quasi-democratic  preference-aggre=
gating systems, like governments are, though of course there are important =
differences in whose preferences are aggregated and how. People get to vote=
 with their money about how companies are run, and a lot of them, intention=
ally or not, seem to have voted for Fink.=C2=A0Still I think it is reasonab=
le to want, as it were, more of a constitution for this sort of thing? Face=
book (sorry, Meta Platforms Inc.) has a certain resemblance to BlackRock: I=
t is an enormous and politically influential aggregator of preferences, it =
is run by one guy, and that guy=E2=80=99s power stems from the (somewhat gr=
udging) revealed preferences of lots of people who use his products. And Fa=
cebook mostly does what Mark Zuckerberg wants. But Zuckerberg, and Facebook=
/Meta, and everyone else, realize that this is an awkward situation, and th=
ey have groped toward giving Facebook more transparency and oversight and=
=C2=A0law. There=E2=80=99s an Oversight Board that gets to review some of F=
acebook=E2=80=99s politically charged decisions; it gets briefing from both=
 sides,=C2=A0publishes written opinions that presumably set precedent,=C2=
=A0and generally acts a little bit like a real court of law.=C2=A0Facebook =
is a quasi-government, or a competitor to governments, or something, and so=
 it sort of conducts itself like a government. I have in the past  suggeste=
d that this is a useful analogy for BlackRock:The point here is just that i=
f a corporation ends up accidentally having some level of systemic power li=
ke this, where its policy decisions have huge effects not just on its share=
holders and customers but on the world as a whole, then perhaps it should t=
ake pains to make those decisions transparently and with public engagement.=
 If your company somehow becomes a quasi-government, perhaps it should act =
quasi-governmentally.It is probably fulfilling to fly around the world tell=
ing companies and governments what to do based on your own personal prefere=
nces, but at some level of power you might want to give that up.
 =20
   =20
      Dual-class stock
   =20
 =20
Meanwhile if you=E2=80=99re a corporate CEO and you don=E2=80=99t want to h=
ave to listen to your shareholders,=C2=A0there is an obvious solution:A rec=
ord number of companies including Chobani, Rent the Runway and Sweetgreen w=
ent public last year with shares that deny voting powers to most investors,=
 a setback for asset managers pushing back against unaccountable corporate =
leadership. =E2=80=A6In 2021, 32 per cent of all US initial public offering=
s were from companies with two share classes, according to Jay Ritter, an I=
PO expert at the University of Florida, with a total of 98 dual-share compa=
nies listed. The percentage and company total were the highest in data goin=
g back to 1980.Large asset managers have fought dual-class share structures=
 for years, arguing that company performance wanes when founders maintain c=
ontrol for too long. BlackRock and other big fund group have urged new comp=
anies to cancel dual-class shares after a few years and establish =E2=80=9C=
one-share, one vote=E2=80=9D accountability. =E2=80=A6=E2=80=9CDual-class s=
tructures are certainly becoming very common,=E2=80=9D said Ofer Eldar, a p=
rofessor at Duke University who has studied dual-class shares. The set up a=
llows a company founder to retain control, he said: =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s a=
lmost as if the firm continues to be private.=E2=80=9DThe schematic way I t=
hink about it is that there are two sorts of big companies in the world. Th=
ere are what you might call legacy public companies, Ford and General Elect=
ric and Goldman Sachs and so forth, which were founded long ago, are owned =
by public shareholders, and are run by professional executives chosen throu=
gh some sort of bureaucratic selection process. And there are what you migh=
t call tech startups, in a very loose sense (Chobani makes yogurt?), which =
continue to be run by their visionary individual founders, and which in som=
e important way continue to be=C2=A0owned=C2=A0by their founders. Some of t=
hese startups are private, with venture capitalists providing money but ver=
y much deferring to the founders; others are public, with public-market inv=
estors providing money but also deferring to the founders through dual-clas=
s stock. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s almost as if the firm continues to be privat=
e.=E2=80=9D They=E2=80=99ll take your money, but they won=E2=80=99t give up=
 control.One thing I will say about this categorization is that you can=E2=
=80=99t be a founder-led startup forever? Henry Ford and Thomas Edison and =
Marcus Goldman have been dead for a long time. It is one thing for a charis=
matic founder to control her company for life even after taking it public; =
it=E2=80=99s another thing for her heirs to keep controlling it forever. Ev=
entually companies have to transition from founder-led startups to professi=
onally run legacy public companies. It used to be that they did that when t=
hey went public. Now it is happening=C2=A0later.
