=C3=A9t=C3=A9 G=C3=A9n=C3=A9rale Bets $5.5 Billion on Car-Leasing Business.=
 =E2=80=9CThe market for table saws is $200-400 million but they cause almo=
st $4 billion in damage annually.=E2=80=9D How=E2=80=99s Martin Shkreli=E2=
=80=99s Wu-Tang Clan album doing? =E2=80=9CMillennia ago, some unnamed inno=
vator created humanity=E2=80=99s most famous early invention: the wheel.=E2=
=80=9DIf you'd like to get=C2=A0Money=C2=A0Stuff=C2=A0in handy email form, =
right in your inbox, please=C2=A0subscribe at this link. Or you can subscri=
be to Money Stuff and other great Bloomberg newsletters here. Thanks![1] I =
feel like I should have a disclaimer here? I=E2=80=99m =E2=80=A6=C2=A0kiddi=
ng? I=E2=80=99m not a professional banker anymore, and certainly not your b=
anker?=C2=A0I suppose my general form of disclaimer here is, like, =E2=80=
=9Cnothing here is any sort of advice that would incur liability if you too=
k it.=E2=80=9D That said, if a company goes and does meme things, and it=E2=
=80=99s a disaster, and its shareholders sue *me* for writing these columns=
, honestly that would be pretty funny, my hat would be off to them a little=
 bit. Still, don=E2=80=99t do that.[2] How does one quantify this? GameStop=
=E2=80=99s wild run in January 2021 really kicked off the modern concept of=
 the meme stock, but you could point to others. Arguably Hertz Global Holdi=
ngs Inc.=E2=80=99s wild 2020 trading *while in bankruptcy* made it the orig=
inal meme stock. Or arguably Elon Musk=E2=80=99s extremely online behavior =
made Tesla Inc. the original meme stock. Arguably AMC=E2=80=99s whole-heart=
ed embrace of its meme-stock status makes it the very memeiest stock these =
days. But GameStop is way up there anyway.[3] Shh, down here I will tell yo=
u the real answer.=C2=A0The real answer is, you buy some September 2017 cal=
l options on Shoe Carnival Inc., an unrelated public company that also sell=
s shoes,=C2=A0which was up 5.5% on Aug. 22, the day that DSW announced its =
earnings. Or Foot Locker was up 4.3% that day. (DSW was up 17.5%.) This is =
called =E2=80=9Cshadow trading,=E2=80=9D using inside information about one=
 company =E2=80=94=C2=A0the one run by your uncle! =E2=80=94=C2=A0to trade =
on *a different but correlated company*.  It is also illegal! The SEC very =
much takes the (correct!) position that using inside information about one =
company to trade options on a comparable company is illegal insider trading=
!=C2=A0Sometimes they catch people who do it! Not that often, though, if we=
 are being honest! Certainly they are way more likely to catch you when you=
 trade call options on *your uncle=E2=80=99s company* than when you trade c=
all options on some random other company in the same industry that happens =
to be correlated! Nothing in this column is ever legal advice, but my occas=
ional=C2=A0footnotes about the smart way to do crime are especially not leg=
al advice! Do not do this! But don=E2=80=99t do what the people in the text=
 allegedly did either.
